      "title": "Direction Cosines",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Direction-Cosines and Direction-Ratios</h3><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"234\" height=\"190\">&nbsp;</p><p>If $\\alpha ,\\beta $ and $\\gamma $ are the angles which is directed line makes with the positive directions of $\\text{x}$-axis, $\\text{y}$-axis and $\\text{z}$-axis respectively, then $\\text{cos}\\alpha ,\\text{cos}\\beta $ and $\\text{cos}\\gamma $ are called the direction-cosines of the line. Direction-cosines are denoted by $l,m,n$ i.e. $l=\\text{cos}\\alpha ,m=\\text{cos}\\beta $ and $n=\\text{cos}\\gamma $.</p><p>Let $\\text{A'OA}$ be a line through $\\text{O}$ with direction-cosines $\\text{cos}\\alpha ,\\text{cos}\\beta ,\\text{cos}\\gamma$ and let $\\text{P}$ be a point on $\\text{A'OA}$ with coordinates $\\left( \\text{x},\\text{y},\\text{z} \\right)$ and position vector $\\vec{r}$</p><p>Then, $\\overrightarrow{\\text{OP}}=\\vec{r}=\\text{x}\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{i}}}\\,+\\text{y}\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{j}}}\\,+\\text{z}\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{k}}}\\,$, and direction-cosines of $\\vec{r}$ are also $\\text{cos}\\alpha ,\\text{cos}\\beta ,\\text{cos}\\gamma $.</p><p>As the x-axis makes angles ${{0}^{0}},\\frac{\\pi }{2},\\frac{\\pi }{2}$ with ox, oy and oz respectively. Therefore direction cosines of $\\text{x}$-axis are $\\text{cos}0,\\text{cos}\\frac{\\pi }{2},\\text{cos}\\frac{\\pi }{2}$ i.e. $1,0,0$, Similarly the direction cosines of $\\text{y}$ and $\\text{z}$-axes are $0,1,0$ and $0,0,1$ respectively.</p><p><strong>Some Results on Direction Cosines :</strong></p><p>Let $\\text{P}\\left( \\text{x},\\text{y},\\text{z} \\right)$ be a point in space such that $\\vec{r}=\\overrightarrow{\\text{OP}}$ has direction cosines $1,\\text{ m},\\text{n}$. Then</p><p>1.$l\\left| \\vec{r}\\left| ,m \\right|\\vec{r}\\left| ,n \\right|\\vec{r} \\right|$ are projections of $\\vec{r}$ on ox,oy,oz respectively, or</p><p>$\\text{x}=\\text{l}\\left| \\vec{r}\\left| ,\\text{y}=\\text{m} \\right|\\vec{r}\\left| ,\\text{z}=\\text{n} \\right|\\vec{r} \\right|$</p><p>2.$\\vec{r}=\\left| {\\vec{r}} \\right|\\left( l\\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+m\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\,+n\\overset{}{\\mathop{k}}\\, \\right)$ and $\\overset{}{\\mathop{r}}\\,=l\\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+m\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\,+n\\overset{}{\\mathop{k}}\\,$</p><p>3.${{\\text{l}}^{2}}+{{\\text{m}}^{2}}+{{\\text{n}}^{2}}=1$</p><p><strong>Direction Ratios :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let $1,m,n$ be direction cosines of a vector $\\vec{r}$ and a,b,c be three numbers such that</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{l}}{\\text{a}}=\\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{b}}=\\frac{\\text{n}}{\\text{c}}$</p><p>Then a,b,c are known as direction ratios or direction numbers of vector $\\vec{r}$.</p>",
